Iceland captain Sara Bjork Gunnarsdottir says winning a claim against former side Lyon for failing to pay her full salary during pregnancy is a "wake-up call" for clubs.

In May 2022, a Fifa tribunal ordered French side Lyon to pay unpaid salaries of more than 82,000 euros (£72,000).

Player's union Fifpro called it a "landmark" case.

"This is not 'just business'," said 32-year-old Gunnarsdottir after the ruling was made public on Tuesday.

"This is about my rights as a worker, as a fertile woman and as a human being."

Writing in the Player's Tribune, the midfielder, who is now at Juventus, added: "The victory felt bigger than me. It felt like a guarantee of financial security for all players who want to have a child during their career. That it's not a 'maybe,' or an unknown.

"But I want to make sure no one has to go through what I went through ever again."

She also tweeted: "This story is bigger than me! It's a wake up-call for all clubs."

>Now Europe has nothing to learn and nothing to take. In my sport - for sure. You yourself write about the "rural holiday" on the Tour de Ski. The fact that this barn of villas and condo of millionaires (yes I'm talking about Davos) does not warm me up personally.

>There are problems with snow in the World Cup stages, it is unclear whether each second stage will take place, cancel or postpone. I talked to my friend in Planitsa - everything is ok there so far but they pray that the weather does not get bad in a month, there are no backup options for skiing races there. In Slovenia no one cares - jumping is the main ski sport there, they will definitely take place. This is not suitable for serious competition!

>What about Vegard Ulwang, who with his latest innovations accelerated the death of ski racing as a show as a television product? Who wants to race 20k or more? It is not for me to explain to you that it is much easier and cheaper to organize a ski sprint show. Well it would be nice to watch these long races - they don't look like that! "Splitting" is like qualification in a sprint - for big experts and connoisseurs, but the main audience will never watch it. Boring!

>FIS is a typical "European institute" in spirit and formally. They are at a dead end and do not know how and where to go further, so they try to hold on to their places tighter and keep what they have not lost yet.

>But Asia is a clean canvas waiting for the first sketch. No one said that Asia would have everything at once. I personally have some free time. We need money, development technology and desire. See Eileen Gu - this is how it's done, this is what Asia is to me! In tired Europe, this is basically impossible, Klaebo is walking down the street in Norway and almost no one recognizes him. I observed and was surprised . If Uno-X pays him half a million a year not to be recognized, it's strange. But very European!

Been a Flames fan since 2007 (maybe underappreciated the Iginla years). Then really got into watching almost every game (starting from the time Flames made the 2015 playoffs with Gaudreau and Monahan).
I think it was around 2017-18 that I may have committed the worse mistake as a sports fan: becoming too attached to them.
Every win was a relief. But every loss made me spiral into meltdowns where I impulsively go onto Capfriendly Armchair GM and come up with stupid trades and buyouts to make me feel better as a person (even though I'm [still] not the biggest fan of Brad Treliving.)
I though it was easy to switch teams to cheer for during this span of sports fandom, but psychologically I couldn't convince myself to actually commit to switching sports teams (only times I cheer for different teams was mostly out of not wanting a team I hate to win the Stanley Cup (ex: last year's Stanley Cup Final, I wanted Colorado to win because I hate to see Tampa Bay win again and trigger more horrible memories of 2004).

I guess I could go into more detail about how this particular Flames season has somehow been more infuriating than previous bad seasons I've watched, but this post is getting too long and depressing (also I question almost every day about whether or not the organization really cares about being competent; forget about winning and competing, I have to think about whether or not they have dignity. 1 - Leonardo Bonucci

The summer of 2017 marks a break with the past for AC Milan: after 31, there are no longer Berlusconi and Galliani to direct the Rossoneri market, as the Milanese club has passed into Chinese hands, while Fassone and Mirabelli ignite fans' dreams with a series of signings that will not have the desired outcome.

The knockout blow is that of Leonardo Bonucci: the Juventus defender is on the outs with Allegri and decides to break with the Bianconeri club. The rift with the Livorno coach a few months earlier and culminating with the famous stool in the stands in Porto was too strong.

In a few hours from Turin to Milan, Milan side, with the Rossoneri pouring 42 million euros into Juventus' coffers. From that moment on, the most expensive purchase in the Diavolo's history. It will not end well, despite the captain's armband on the arm of the national team central.

The full schedule can be seen here:
>https://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/Sessions/Tournament/14590

Rating: 6/10

>Eagles vs. Giants
One of the NFL's fiercest rivalries on the big stage. Both teams have young and electrifying QBs but to me the team with the better defensive showing is the one that will pull through. That team, with the home crowd on their side, should be the Eagles, and additionally the Eagles offense is more proven than the Giants, giving them the double edge. Regardless of what happens this should be a very close and heated matchup and I'm looking forward to seeing both teams go at it. Should be fun and close.

As much as I would like to say the Cowboys are being overlooked here, I can't agree. They're not on the same level as the 49ers on paper and we'll see why. The 49ers are simply the most balanced team in the NFL on paper, both offense and defense at elite levels and should prevail in the end. Regardless, I think this game has the potential to be better than others may think.

Tamanishiki was promoted when the rank wasn't formalized. He won a bunch of yusho as an ozeki so they decided, ok, good enough. That was before the 6-tournament/15-day era anyway.

I don't know how the fuck Kashiwado got promoted. I guess the JSA just thought the sport would be better off with two yokozuna, so he was promoted at the same time as Taiho.

Comparing with this year, and the more I look at it the more it seems like there could be a similar situation here
A lot of strong performances in the top 8 or so makushita ranks and, possibly, not enough movement above them to warrant enough promotions

Okinoumi intai, Kaisho can't salvage that with 5-10, that's two spots open. Takakento and Tsushimanada could both scrape by with a win or two apiece, but they're fucked if they don't, and after that it's a shitload of guesswork and what-if, and digging into precedent to see what caused the exception cases
The J8 pair can save rank by winning once (and getting demoted from there by going 5-10 is rare, a rule with a handful of exceptions), and basically same with Tochimusashi (nobody's been demoted at 5-10 from J7 in forty years) and Churanoumi
So for the other plausible other demos we have Chiyosakae and Terutsuyoshi, who are fucked for sure if they don't win, and aren't even solid if they win out (6-9 for j11 has generally been enough to save rank recently, but the circumstances for each would take more time here than I care to spend)

I'll split the difference and assume that four spots are opening up in Juryo, so who might be going up?
Assuming losses for every man in the promotion zone in picrel, not a single person's performance forces the issue and guarantees a promotion. Tamashoho, Tokushoryu, and Tsukahara are the only ones who are basically locked for promotion given the combination of position and performance; Tomokaze, Fujiseiun and Tokihayate would be hoping to win and either see their competitors lose, or beat them themselves. Ochiai's 7-0 stands out like a sore thumb here, and unless somehow the association fucks up and allows all six of these guys to win and muddies the water big-time, he's Juryo in March
Nobody with a match left and a promotion chance is in the listing for tomorrow so day 15 should be a riveting one to watch from div 3 onwards

Most of the bodies were found in barrels in an abandoned bank vault in Snowtown, South Australia, hence the names given in the press for the murders. Only one of the victims was killed in Snowtown itself, which is approximately 140 kilometres (87 miles) north of Adelaide, and neither the twelve victims nor the three perpetrators were from the town. Although motivation for the murders is unclear, the killers were led by Bunting to believe that the victims were paedophiles, homosexuals, or "weak". In the case of some victims, the murders were preceded by torture, and efforts were made to appropriate victims' identities, social security payments and bank accounts.

Although initially the notoriety of the murders led to a short-term economic boost from tourists visiting Snowtown, it created a stigma, with authorities considering a change of the town's name and identity.

two things: the Cowboys are a fairly recent team by NFL standards. The original owner teamed up with the Chiefs owner to combine the AFL and NFL into one league. To get this to take off, they came up with this whole BS America's Team crap. That's all it was. It was a promo to make the league popular. These two also came up with the term Super Bowl, because Super was a fancy popular English term at the time. So this whole Cowboys meme was invented for commercial purposes.

Not liking the Niners is a more recent thing. Some teams have always been the bad guys, like the Raiders. Most successful teams that play the game right are liked by most fans. The Niners fall into that category. While everyone remembers Joe Montana, a lot of fans love Ronnie Lott, a tough as hell defensive player who famously had the tip of his broken finger cut off and taped the two fingers together so that he wouldn't miss a playoff game. That is playing the game right, right there. But ever since Kaepernick, it has been fashionable to hate the Niners.
